<div class="container">
    <h1>Welcome to Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)</h1>
    <p>This chapter introduces the fundamentals of <strong>Object-Oriented Programming</strong>, a programming paradigm based on the concept of <strong>objects</strong> that contain data and behavior.</p>

    <h2>What You Will Learn</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Classes:</strong> Blueprints for creating objects.</li>
        <li><strong>Constructors:</strong> Methods to initialize objects.</li>
        <li><strong>Objects:</strong> Instances of classes.</li>
        <li><strong>Encapsulation:</strong> Protecting object data with controlled access.</li>
        <li><strong>Polymorphism:</strong> Ability for objects to take many forms (method overloading/overriding).</li>
        <li><strong>Inheritance:</strong> Creating new classes based on existing ones.</li>
        <li><strong>Abstraction:</strong> Hiding complex implementation details and exposing only essential features.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Each section will include clear explanations, C# examples, and exercises to practice your skills.</p>

